Tidyverse: dplyr

Bernard Ade

10-20-2016

Dplyr is a powerful R package for data manipulation. It is widely known that Data Scientists spend a bulk of their time cleaning, preparing and munging data before performing data analysis. Dplyr provides some great functions that makes it easy to manipulate data. In this post I will demonstrate some of the core verbs that makes it easy to describe the components of data wrangling in an intuitive fashion. These core verbs include: * Select * Groupby * Filter * Arrange * Mutate * Summarise

This introduction is just a tip of the iceberg of the capabailites of dplyr. For more information check out the following the resources.

R for Data Science

Load libraries

library(dplyr) # data wrangling
library(lubridate) # lubridate is great for working with date and time.

Select

Select is used to subset columns from a dataframe.

#lets select the columns Category, Product name and Sales
subset = select(superstore, Category, Product.Name, Sales)
head(subset)
# We can select to isolate a range of columns, from Country to Region
subset = select(superstore, Country:Region)
head(subset)
# We can use the 'contains' method to select columns that matches a keyword
subset = select(superstore, contains('customer'))
head(subset)

Filter

Filter is useful for returning rows that satisfy a defined condition.

# lets filter only the western region
west = filter(superstore, Region == 'West')
head(west)
#lets filter rows that matches the category furniture and sales greater than 500.
filter_sales = filter(superstore, Category == 'Furniture' & Sales > 500)
head(filter_sales)

Pipes

At this point I will like to introduce the concept pipes. Pipes are extremely useful for chaining functions for ease of readability.

#With %>% (pipes) we can chain methods for ease of readability
filter_sales = 
    filter_sales %>% 
    select(Sales, Region)
head(filter_sales)

Summarise

Summarise is useful for aggregating data into a single row using a varierty of math functions.

# lets summarise the number of orders
count = summarise(superstore, orders = n())
count
# lets summarise the value of average order
average_order = summarise(superstore, average_order = sum(Sales) / n())
average_order

Arrange

The arrange function is used to re-order rows.

# lets sort rows(ascending) by profit and display columns region and profit
profit_asc = 
    superstore %>%
    select(Region, Profit) %>%
    arrange(Profit)
head(profit_asc)
# lets sort rows (descending) by profit and display columns region and profit
profit_desc = 
    superstore %>%
    select(Region, Profit) %>%
    arrange(desc(Profit))
head(profit_desc)

Mutate

Mutate is used to transform existing columns to create new columns.

# lets create a new column that calculates the profit ratio
profit_ratio = 
    superstore %>%
    mutate(profit_ratio = Profit/Sales)%>%
    select(Profit, Sales, profit_ratio)
head(profit_ratio)
# lets convert order date and ship date to a date type using Lubridate and calculate the date difference to obtain days to ship.
days_to_ship = 
    superstore %>%
        mutate(days_to_ship = mdy(Ship.Date) - mdy(Order.Date)) %>%
        select(Order.Date, Ship.Date, days_to_ship, Ship.Mode)
head(days_to_ship)

Group By

Groupby is useful for grouping data by one or more variables.

# lets group states and calculate top 10 performing states in sales
group_by(superstore, State) %>%
    summarise(total_sales = sum(Sales)) %>%
    top_n(10, total_sales)%>%
    arrange(desc(total_sales))
